The paper presents a study of generative modeling approaches for Multiple-Instance Learning (MIL) problems, specifically in the context of diagnosing neuromuscular disorders using sets of motor unit potential trains (MUPTs) detected within a muscle. This work involves examining a variety of model structures and components, and evaluating the proposed methods on MUPT datasets and the MUSK1 dataset. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), followed by cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), cs.CV (Computer Vision), cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), and cs.BIO (Computational Biology).
